    <stitle>DT 466 / DT 570 / HT 570 Diesel Engine Diagnostic Manual - 2004 Emissions with EGR - Engine Symptoms
        Diagnostics - Problems and Conditions - Lube Oil in Coolant
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="4">
        <title>Lube Oil in Coolant</title>
        <para id="s27004022">
            <title>Symptom</title>
        </para>
        <para>Coolant contaminated with lube oil will have oil in the deaeration tank.</para>
        <randlist type="bullet">
            <title>Cause</title>
            <item>
                <para>Oil cooler</para>
            </item>
        </randlist>
        <randlist type="bullet">
            <title>Tools</title>
            <item>
                <para>Oil cooler pressure test plate</para>
            </item>
            <item>
                <para>Air pressure regulator</para>
            </item>
        </randlist>
        <para>
            <title>Procedure</title>
        </para>
        <figure id="f27004" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figh05/H05004.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Deaeration tank fill position</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Deaeration tank cap</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Deaeration tank</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">MAXIMUM coolant level mark</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">ADD coolant level mark</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>To avoid serious personal injury, possible death and damage to the engine:</para>
                <randlist type="bullet">
                    <item>
                        <para>Always allow the engine to cool for 15 minutes.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Wrap a thick cloth around the cap.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Loosen cap slowly a quarter to half turn.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Pause for a moment to avoid water or steam scalding.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Continue to turn the cap and remove.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Never add cold coolant to a hot engine. This can result in a cracked cylinder head or
                            crankcase.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Never use water as a coolant substitute.</para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Verify if coolant is contaminated by inspecting deaeration tank for presence of oil.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Place a coolant drain pan under the oil system module.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f27004" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figh05/H05011.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="312px"/>
            <caption>Coolant drain plug</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the coolant drain plug located at the bottom of the oil system module. Drain
                coolant
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Replace O-ring with a new O-ring when installing the coolant drain plug.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f27004" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figh31/H31413.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Removing oil cooler</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the eight bolts (M8 x 20) securing the oil cooler to the oil cooler housing. Separate
                the oil cooler from the oil cooler housing.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f27004" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figh13/H13032.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="312px"/>
            <caption>Checking the oil cooler for internal leakage</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Test plate set</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Air pressure regulator</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Coolant port (open)</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Oil port</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Pressure test the oil cooler following the procedure in the Engine Service Manual. If a leak
                is noticed, replace the oil cooler.
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
